"Finger A., Schmitt T., Emmanuel Zachos F., Meyer M., Assmann T., Christian Habel J.","The genetic status of the violet copper Lycaena helle - A relict of the cold past in times of global warming",2009,"Ecography","32","3",,"382","390",,,10.1111/j.1600-0587.2008.05766.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-67649946055&partnerID=40&md5=46d8bf88e75f6d767fa87467cc3d264b","ETH Zürich, ITES - Ecosystem Management, CH-8092 Zürich, Switzerland; Univ. Trier, Biogeography, DE-54296 Trier, Germany; Zoological Inst., Christian-Albrechts-Univ., DE-24118 Kiel, Germany; Musée National d'Histoire Naturelle, Section Zoologie des Invertébrés, LU-2160 Luxembourg, Luxembourg; Univ. Lüneburg, Inst. of Ecology, DE-21335 Lüneburg, Germany","Finger, A., ETH Zürich, ITES - Ecosystem Management, CH-8092 Zürich, Switzerland; Schmitt, T., Univ. Trier, Biogeography, DE-54296 Trier, Germany; Emmanuel Zachos, F., Zoological Inst., Christian-Albrechts-Univ., DE-24118 Kiel, Germany; Meyer, M., Musée National d'Histoire Naturelle, Section Zoologie des Invertébrés, LU-2160 Luxembourg, Luxembourg; Assmann, T., Univ. Lüneburg, Inst. of Ecology, DE-21335 Lüneburg, Germany; Christian Habel, J.","Rising temperatures and agricultural changes (intensification and succession on fallow land) during the last few decades have caused a strong decline of moist and cool sites on nutrient-poor grasslands and species depending on these habitats. We tested the effects of habitat deterioration on a local and regional scale in such a species, the highly endangered butterfly Lycaena helle, which was more widely distributed over central Europe during the postglacial period, but has recently become restricted to some remnants. We analysed five polymorphic microsatellite loci in 220 individuals sampled at ten different localities. The study sites in Germany, Luxembourg and Belgium are geographically split into three mountain regions: the Ardennes, the Eifel and the Westerwald; the latter is separated from the other two by the river Rhine. A comparatively high genetic diversity was detected in all local populations and genetic differentiation was found among the Ardennes, the Eifel and the Westerwald (F CT: 0.084). The genetic differentiation among all populations (F ST: 0.137) underlines natural and anthropogenic habitat fragmentation. While ongoing gene flow seems to exist among the Eifel populations indicating the only intact metapopulation, a high genetic differentiation in the Ardennes and the Westerwald indicates a disruption of population connectivity. Our genetic data obtained on different spatial scales show the genetic consequence of long-term isolation and should trigger necessary conservation measures at the metapopulation level. © 2009 Ecography.",,"agricultural intensification; butterfly; connectivity; conservation status; copper; endangered species; environmental degradation; fallow; gene flow; global warming; habitat conservation; habitat fragmentation; habitat quality; metapopulation; mountain region; polymorphism; Postglacial; relict species; species conservation; succession; temperature effect; temperature gradient; Ardennes [Western Europe]; Belgium; Benelux; Central Europe; Eifel; Eurasia; Europe; Germany; Luxembourg [Benelux]; Rhenish Schiefergebirge; Rhine River; Rhineland-Palatinate; Western Europe; Westerwald; Lycaena helle",,,,,,"Anthes, N., Fartmann, T., Hermann, G., Kaule, G., Combining larval habitat quality and metapopulation structure - The key for succesful management of pre-alpine Euphydryas aurinia colonies (2003) Journal of Insect Conservation, 7 (3), pp. 175-185. , DOI 10.1023/A:1027330422958; Bachelard, P., Descimon, H., Lycaena helle (Denis & Schiffermüller) dans le Massif Central (France): Une étude écogéographique. (Lepidoptera: Lycaenidae) (1999) Linn. Belg., 17, pp. 23-41; Baguette, M., Neve, G., Adult movements between populations in the specialist butterfly Proclossiana eunomia (Lepidoptera, Nymphalidae) (1994) Ecological Ent